<p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 624.00px; height: 4.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image1.png" style="width: 624.00px; height: 4.00px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title="horizontal line"></span></p> 
</div><h2 class="c57" id="h.cur88z83k4v2"><span class="c31">Winter, Year 2</span></h2><p class="c27"><span class="c37 c44">ccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccc</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">A thin wind wafts over the mountainpeaks. &nbsp;At this elevation, breathing becomes difficult, even for Crag. &nbsp;For all the pride you may have in the gifts granted you by The Path your ancestors trod, you are forced to concede mastery of these peaks to other creatures. &nbsp;Too bad for them that their overspecialization has left them vulnerable.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You can see them clearly, sitting in the rising sun. &nbsp;Squat. &nbsp;Massive. &nbsp;Their glassy eyes observe their surroundings, but don&rsquo;t search them; they are confident in their position in this food chain. No Fear.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">You are the rocks. &nbsp;You are the boulders. &nbsp;You are the scree, the sleet, the gravel, the dust.<br>You are the whisper of air, the grit within, the slow force which silently erodes the mightiest mountains.<br>You are tension. &nbsp;The singing torque. &nbsp;You are the sharpened point.<br>You are killing intent.<br><br>Your quarry tilts its head, its bulbous eye looking straight at you, but still unseeing.<br>You are the correct moment.<br><br>The shaft springs from your bow, launching itself towards the presented weak point. Before it even lands, however, you have made yourself one with the terrain once more. &nbsp;A wet thud, a maddened screech, is all you need to hear to bring a wicked smile to your face.<br>You shift several feet to the side before peeking once again. &nbsp;Sure enough, your arrow is lodged firmly in what was once an eye, now just a ruptured tangle of flesh in a gaping socket. &nbsp;As you watch, two more shafts spring from its back. &nbsp;If your quarry were a prey creature, it and the rest of its knot would have already begun flight. &nbsp;Their confidence, their arrogant assumption of superiority, has now led to confusion. &nbsp;It is their ultimate downfall.<br>It turns, looking for the source of the pain in its back. &nbsp;Giving you a perfect line on the </span><span class="c19 c11">other</span><span class="c14">&nbsp;eyeball.<br>The impact of the second shaft sends it sprawling. &nbsp;Blind, pained, it thrashes out in all directions. &nbsp;A massive, rime-coated leg thrashes and strikes one of its number. &nbsp;This, finally, seems to be what sets the rest of your quarries into flight.<br>You stand. &nbsp;The time for stealth is over. &nbsp;<br><br>You fill your hand with shafts. &nbsp;Draw. Aim. Release. Draw. Aim. Release. Draw. Aim. Release.<br>By the time you fill your hand once more, the damage is done. &nbsp;More than a dozen arrows have sprouted among your targets in half as many seconds. &nbsp;The largest of their number, the one you blinded, still thrashes. &nbsp;Two others lie still.<br><br>You whistle into the wind. &nbsp;Let the rest run. &nbsp;This is more than enough for today.<br>You scramble down the mountainside. &nbsp;Your pace is sure, your movement unhindered. &nbsp;In one smooth, practiced motion, you draw your kuthe as you descend. &nbsp;<br><br>Your quarry is blind, but still dangerous. &nbsp;Its thrashing is not death throes, but a maddened attempt to lash out at anything, everything, that is within its reach. &nbsp;Its massive maw bites down on a helpless boulder, coating it with ice. &nbsp;<br><br>You leap upon the creature. &nbsp;Your flesh burns, a fierce, unyielding cold sapping the life from your skin. &nbsp;Your blood sings. &nbsp;The pain is distant, a nagging reminder rather than an urgent warning. &nbsp;You are alive.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">Your kuthe bites deep in the creature&rsquo;s gut. &nbsp;It screams, maw turning to engulf you. <br>Perfect.<br>Your blow is quick. &nbsp;Precise. &nbsp;Through the roof of the mouth. &nbsp;Into the brain.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">It sags around you. &nbsp;Dead weight draping on top of you. &nbsp;Icy mucus coats you, further stinging your ice burns. &nbsp;It&rsquo;s no matter. &nbsp;No pain could outweigh the joy in your blood.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">Sadly, your euphoria begins to fade. &nbsp;The hunt is done. &nbsp;Now, a far more onerous task remains. &nbsp;<br>Oh well. &nbsp;It was fun while it lasted.</span></p> 
<p class="c1"><span class="c14"></span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">You are </span><span class="c56 c32">Stalker Embebi</span><span class="c14">, and now that you and your small hunting detachment have finished tracking and killing your quarry, now you have to deal with the fact that you&rsquo;ve got three glacier toads to gut and clean, and unfortunately, these things are about 60% gut. &nbsp;<br>At least you don&rsquo;t have to do it alone. &nbsp;Jambor and Kirkov are already starting to work on the toads they felled. &nbsp;Juveniles, by the look of them, but Juvenile glacier toads are still nearly as big as a Crag. &nbsp;The one before you is twice your size, and probably four times your weight. &nbsp;And after you remove the inedible and poisonous parts, maybe it&rsquo;ll be only twice your weight. &nbsp;Thankfully, that&rsquo;s what the sled is for. &nbsp;You can drag that much, no problem.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You flip your lith from your belt. &nbsp;Time to get to work.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">More than an hour later, the three of you are finally plodding back into base camp, your spoils dragged behind you. &nbsp;Your return is noted by exclamations both excited and disappointed. &nbsp;Plenty of meat on a glacier toad, so everyone will sleep with full bellies tonight. &nbsp;Too bad the texture is like hard snot. &nbsp;Taste, not much better. &nbsp;You drop the sled to the side, leaving it for whatever poor soul has mess duty this rotation. &nbsp;You have other things to attend to.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19 c36">&ldquo;&lt;Attention! I&rsquo;m looking for Gustav. &nbsp;He has returned, yes?&gt;&rdquo;</span><sup class="c19 c36"><a href="#ftnt1" id="ftnt_ref1">[1]</a></sup></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">One of those milling about, a young Crag tending to the fire, is the first to respond.<br></span><span class="c19 c47">&ldquo;&lt;Yes. &nbsp;He returned without incident. &nbsp;He&rsquo;s currently using the facilities.&gt;&rdquo;</span><sup class="c19 c47"><a href="#ftnt2" id="ftnt_ref2">[2]</a></sup></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">You give her a curt nod. &nbsp;</span><span class="c19 c36">&ldquo;&lt;When he&rsquo;s finished, tell him to head to the main tent. &nbsp;I&rsquo;ll want to debrief him directly.&gt;&rdquo;</span><sup class="c19 c36"><a href="#ftnt3" id="ftnt_ref3">[3]</a></sup></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">She nods back. &nbsp;Satisfied, you proceed to the aforementioned tent. &nbsp;&lsquo;Tent&rsquo; is a bit of a misnomer, in this case; it&rsquo;s more of a big tarp that keeps the snow off what few maps and notes you brought with you. &nbsp;Thankfully, the local terrain provides an abundance of paperweights. &nbsp;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You look over the etchings made of the local area. &nbsp;Sure enough, Gustav already left his new ones here. &nbsp;They paint much the same picture as all the other ones; Mountain, mountain, and more boring mountain.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">You huff, your breath steaming from your nostrils. &nbsp;While the last few months have been, quite frankly, relaxing compared to all the unorthodox missions you&rsquo;ve had to deal with in recent times, you wish you had a little more to show for it. &nbsp;So far, this expedition has had few of the exciting surprises you had discovered on your last trip around the mountain. &nbsp;You can&rsquo;t shake the nagging thought that it might be because there are some truths to the scandalous accusation leveled by the First Among Scholars; &nbsp;you don&rsquo;t entirely know </span><span class="c19 c11">what</span><span class="c14">&nbsp;you are looking for out here. &nbsp;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">Well, that&rsquo;s not entirely true. &nbsp;You know what you&rsquo;re looking for&hellip; you&rsquo;re just concerned that some of the more subtle clues to find it might be escaping you.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You pick up one of the etchings. &nbsp;It seems to indicate a narrow pass, banded with colorful layers of metamorphic substrate, and rendered in fine detail; this shows a great deal of skill in the will of the etcher, &nbsp;but it&rsquo;s otherwise indistinguishable from the innumerable other passes you witnessed. &nbsp;You wonder what-</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">Wait. &nbsp;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">Close to the bottom of the pass&hellip; the walls narrow, except for a small entry point. &nbsp;It doesn&rsquo;t fit with the rest of the pass&rsquo; shape. &nbsp;It almost looks like&hellip;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c17">&ldquo;It looks like it was willed, quiaff?&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">You </span><span class="c19 c11">very pointedly</span><span class="c14">&nbsp;do not jump, start, or otherwise react to the voice suddenly appearing in your ear. &nbsp;It would be unseemly. &nbsp;You do concede to cursing internally, however. &nbsp;&ldquo;Ninth hell claim him,&rdquo; it goes.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You turn around with all the grace you can muster, looking down at none other than Gustaf, your second for this venture. &nbsp;You look into his smug face. &nbsp;It&rsquo;s curious; he has somehow mastered the art of looking smug without smiling, tilting his eyebrows, or otherwise indulging in the typical symptoms of smugness. &nbsp;He&rsquo;s just somehow got a resting smug face. &nbsp;You have to admit, it impresses you.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">Sometimes, you&rsquo;d counter smug with smug, but you think you&rsquo;ll let it pass in this instance. &nbsp;You&rsquo;re too curious about what it is he&rsquo;s found.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c3">&ldquo;Aff. &nbsp;And a strong will, to boot. &nbsp;I was told your expedition was nonsit. &nbsp;So that must mean that you were uncertain about what this meant&hellip; or you planned on keeping this to yourself? Claim the challenge for yourself?&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c17">&ldquo;I planned on keeping it to US, Stalkact. I wanted to make sure you had the opportunity to decide what to do without having to worry about&hellip; general opinion.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">...That&rsquo;s some concerning wording. &nbsp;That, and the fact that he&rsquo;s keeping to civlang. &nbsp;It means that whatever he wants to talk about, it&rsquo;s going to get complicated. &nbsp;It might even get political.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You purse your lips. You hate it when things get political.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c3">&ldquo;What do you mean? What possible &lsquo;opinion&rsquo; could there be about a hole in a ravine? A hole is a hole.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">He closes his eyes, and shakes his head. &nbsp;You hate it when he does that. &nbsp;It means he&rsquo;s going to talk up at you. &nbsp;You&rsquo;ve long suspected that there&rsquo;s likely a fair share of Bakshish lineage in him; it would explain his small (by your standards, anyway) stature, and also his general&hellip; know-it-all-itude. &nbsp;You wish you knew a better word for that.<br>As infuriating as that is, however, it&rsquo;s that general&hellip; knowiness?... that made you decide to make him your second. &nbsp;It might be difficult to work with, but ancestors condemn if it doesn&rsquo;t help get results.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c17">&ldquo;Stalkact, what I think we&rsquo;ve found here is incontrovertible proof of the direction that some of our wayward kin may have travelled. &nbsp;If they truly sheltered in that pass, then we know more than ever where they may be now; the ravine lets out in only one area, a few miles from here. &nbsp;If there&rsquo;s any trace of their passage left, it will be our best chance to track them down.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19 c40">&nbsp;</span><span class="c3">&ldquo;-That only sounds like good news. &nbsp;Why would you want to try to conceal that?&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">His eyes tweak. &nbsp;You can&rsquo;t tell if he&rsquo;s frustrated, or sorrowful..</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c17">&ldquo;...I know one of our main objectives out here is to try to find those who may have fled from Eschaton, or perhaps even survived the death of one of the other settlements. &nbsp;But&hellip; to be fully frank, Stalkact, I question the wisdom of this objective.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You raise an eyebrow, but say nothing in return. &nbsp;He starts to look&hellip; worried? &nbsp;You&rsquo;re pretty sure that&rsquo;s worried.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c17">&ldquo;I mean, I just don&rsquo;t think that the Named may have really thought out the consequences. &nbsp;What if we do find them, but they&rsquo;ve expired? If we were too late? &nbsp;It would be a terrible blow to morale. &nbsp;It would be yet another failure to heap upon the recent mistakes that the others blame on the Aggro. &nbsp;The Named may have just unwittingly set you up to be yet another poor example.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">You scoff. &nbsp;</span><span class="c19 c36">&ldquo;That&rsquo;s ridiculous. &nbsp;I believe you are far overstating their reaction. &nbsp;All knew that when we started this expedition, there was a very likely chance that we would only find tragedy; &nbsp;Look at how difficult it was for those in Eschaton to survive in the wake of the Extermination. &nbsp;Poor souls out in the drifts would have a far more difficult prospect before them. &nbsp;In truth, until </span><span class="c10">we</span><span class="c3">&nbsp;discovered some of our number surviving in the lowlands, everyone had more or less written them off as dead already! &nbsp;I can see little logic in the other bloodlines accusing us for confirming their assumptions.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19 c40">&ldquo;... That is fair enough, Stalkact. &nbsp;But have you considered the consequences should we </span><span class="c19 c40 c11">succeed</span><span class="c17">?&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c3">&ldquo;What? &nbsp;What nonsense talk is this? &nbsp;The consequences of being Named? &nbsp;I already am fully aware of the difficulties that such responsibility presents. &nbsp;I-&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c17">&ldquo;Neg, Stalkact. &nbsp;Not your Naming. &nbsp;The Consequences for Eschaton, should you succeed.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You furrow your brow. &nbsp;Now he&rsquo;s just talking in puzzles. &nbsp;And he&rsquo;s stopped explaining, instead just looking at you, waiting for a response he knows won&rsquo;t come.. &nbsp;You know what game he&rsquo;s playing, and refuse to play it. &nbsp; A coy smile winds onto your face.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c3">&ldquo;Oh, thinking of success, I had quite a successful hunt. &nbsp;I understand you&rsquo;ve become quite proficient in preparing toadflesh, quiaff? &nbsp;Perhaps you can give the Mess a hand, since it seems like you don&rsquo;t have any more to say.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">Hah! He blanches at that. &nbsp;You even get a little lip curl for your troubles. &nbsp;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19 c40">&ldquo;Fine, fine. &nbsp;I&rsquo;ll explain myself. &nbsp;Consider this, Stalkact. &nbsp;What if we find these wayward kin, and far from having perished, they have perhaps survived? &nbsp;Or even thrived? &nbsp;As you yourself pointed out, Eschaton has had difficulties aplenty surviving in the wake of the Extermination. &nbsp;If we were to further burden it with the untold number we may find, will it be able to bear the strain? &nbsp;Or what if they don&rsquo;t </span><span class="c19 c40 c11">want</span><span class="c17">&nbsp;to return? It&rsquo;s unheard of, but we&rsquo;ve encountered far stranger things as of late. &nbsp;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c17">There are any number of ways that our success at this mission could be even more of a tragedy than failure, Stalkact. &nbsp;I have no doubt that the Named intended well, but&hellip; I cannot shake the thought that perhaps this part of the mission, this search for the lost, may have been made in haste. &nbsp;I hate to speak it, but we have seen a fair share of that of late, as well.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c17">Which is why it may be in the best interest of all involved to&hellip; show patience and due consideration, in regard to this pass. &nbsp;After all, it may be nothing. &nbsp;An illusion of will. &nbsp;None would question you if you would decide to overlook it. &nbsp; Fewer still, if they were unaware that there was anything to overlook.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">Fifth hell.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">There was a reason you decided to make Gustaf your second. &nbsp;This is the reason. &nbsp;That mind of his is twisted, but in all the right ways. &nbsp;He sees things, like this. &nbsp;Considers what no one else would consider considering. &nbsp;And best of all, he has the tenacity to speak of the unconsiderable. </span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">He isn&rsquo;t wrong. As in everything you have been caught up in lately, you tread on uncertain ground. &nbsp;No one has ever had to search for kin like this before. &nbsp;No one has had to an opportunity to consider the consequences of something like this. &nbsp;Certainly, the first re-integration occurred without notable issue, but one occurrence does not a pattern make. And the consequences of a fragment that would not want to re-integrate? &nbsp;A&hellip; a </span><span class="c19 c11">rebellious</span><span class="c14">&nbsp;splinter of kin? &nbsp;You can scarcely even put the thought into the right context. &nbsp;It&rsquo;s almost nonsensical.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">You also know that he&rsquo;s right about the Named. &nbsp;This would not be the first action that they&rsquo;ve rushed into lately without considering all of the possible outcomes. &nbsp;Indeed, desperate for victories, they may have felt forced to commit to something, </span><span class="c19 c11">anything</span><span class="c14">, to try and prove their ability, to restore confidence.<br>You can&rsquo;t disagree. &nbsp;His logic is ironclad. &nbsp;It would be far wiser to wait on this, to fully consider the outcomes, to allow Eschaton, now barely just recovering, an opportunity to regain its footing before introducing any more wild variables.<br>The wisest course of action would be to fully consider this action, no matter how many days, weeks, even years it might take.<br></span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">It takes you thirty seconds.</span></p> 
<p class="c1"><span class="c14"></span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c3">&ldquo;OI! ATTEND! Stalkers, we&rsquo;ve got a prime lead on our wayward souls! I want three teams of our best trackers, ready to head out in the next hour! Grab Gear, Haul Rear, Aff?!&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c1"><span class="c3"></span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">The responding ACK, AFF echoes over the mountainsides, as two dozen Crag scramble from their duties to retrieve weapons, armor, and equipment. &nbsp;You look out over the action, pride and confidence swelling in your heart.</span></p> 
<p class="c1"><span class="c14"></span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c3">&ldquo;...You&rsquo;re right, Gustaf. &nbsp;It would have been far wiser to wait. &nbsp;Which is why we can&rsquo;t. &nbsp;Only Aggro would be so foolish as to attempt such an audacious action. &nbsp;Only Aggro will save those souls.&rdquo;</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c14">You turn to look at him, only to find that there&rsquo;s nothing to look at. &nbsp;He&rsquo;s nowhere to be seen.</span></p> 
<p class="c8"><span class="c19">-How in the fourth hell does he </span><span class="c19 c11">do</span><span class="c14">&nbsp;that?</span></p> 
